EAST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: THOUSAND OAKS; POOL OF 300 HELPERS TOO FEW FOR PLAZA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEPHANIE SIMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Civic Arts Plaza will not open for another three months, but already 300 
volunteers have signed up to work as ushers, tour guides and all-around 
helpers. 
</P>
<P>
 But they need reinforcements.The Friends of the Civic Arts Plaza group is 
seeking more volunteers. Members must pay $10 in annual dues and devote their 
time to helping the cultural center run smoothly. For all that work, they do 
get some perks -- ushers can slip into the theater and see shows for free, as 
long as seats are available. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's a great opportunity to get involved with the arts in Thousand Oaks," 
said JoAnn Arguelles, who serves as secretary for the group. "We're pretty 
excited that we have so many people -- and we'll use them all." 
</P>
<P>
 The Friends will hold an introductory meeting 7 p.m. Aug. 4 at City Hall. For 
more information, call Marianne Corney at 496-8688. STEPHANIE SIMON 
