<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEST VALLEY FOCUS: CHATSWORTH; CHILD-CARE CENTER AT TRAIN DEPOT OKD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SUSAN BYRNES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A city zoning administrator granted final approval to the Los Angeles 
Department of Transportation on Monday to construct a child-care center and 
historic depot at the Chatsworth Metrolink station. 
</P>
<P>
 "I think it's a good project," said associate zoning administrator Horace 
Tramel at a public hearing at the Sherman Oaks Woman's Club. "I think it will 
encourage the use of rapid transit." The 12,700-square-foot center will provide 
day care for up to 90 children, giving priority to parents who ride Metrolink 
and other mass transit. In addition, the zoning administrator approved a 
variance for construction of a 4,000-square-foot office space in the train 
station depot. 
</P>
<P>
 The first of its kind in Los Angeles County, the project faced no community 
opposition. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's a real community project," said Francine Oschin, legislative deputy to 
Councilman Hal Bernson. "Even the most vocal opponents of everything in 
Chatsworth are behind this." 
</P>
<P>
 In addition to indoor and outdoor space for children age 6 months to 5 years, 
the center will house office and retail space. 
</P>
<P>
 "The sooner it can be up and running, the happier we will be," Oschin said at 
the hearing. 
</P>
<P>
 The design of the depot recalls Chatsworth's original Southern Pacific 
Station, which was torn down in the early part of this century. The depot will 
replace a platform and canopy which opened at the station on 21510 Devonshire 
St. in October, 1992. 
</P>
<P>
 Of the 400 commuters who use the Chatsworth station each day, the majority 
park at the station and take the train to Simi Valley, department of 
transportation officials said. 
</P>
<P>
 The others arrive at the station from locations outside the San Fernando 
Valley and take taxis to their workplaces. 
</P>
<P>
 The child-care center will operate from 5:30 a.m. to 7:30 p.m. Monday through 
Friday. Project planners expect to break ground on the center before summer's 
end and predict that the day-care center could be in operation as early as the 
spring of 1995. 
</P>
<P>
 A similar project for the Sylmar Metrolink station is in the planning stages. 
SUSAN BYRNES 
</P>
</TEXT>
