<HEADLINE>
<P>
UNEMPLOYMENT RATE UP SLIGHTLY TO 5.8%; ECONOMY: EXPERTS SAY THE JUNE INCREASE 
IS DUE TO SEASONAL FACTORS AND THAT THE LOCAL ECONOMY IS STILL MAKING A 
RECOVERY. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GREG JOHNSON, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Orange County's unemployment rate inched up to 5.8% in June. Observers linked 
the slight rise to temporary job losses when many workers, including school 
system employees, are off for the summer. 
</P>
<P>
 The number of unemployed people in the county rose to 76,200 last month, 
compared to 71,200 in May, according to figures released Monday by the state 
Employment Development Department's Anaheim office. The county's unemployment 
rate stood at 5.4% in May. 
</P>
<P>
 The county's jobless rate of 5.8% last month compared favorably with a rate of 
6.2% nationwide and an 8.7% rate for California. Los Angeles County's 
unemployment rate was 10.1% in June. 
</P>
<P>
 Observers said the slight month-to-month increase in Orange County doesn't 
necessarily signal problems for the local economy, which is recovering from a 
recession that began in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
 "We are still on an upward part of the curve, but the slope isn't that 
dramatic," said Anil Puri, head of the economics department at Cal State 
Fullerton. 
</P>
<P>
 Puri said the June report confirms that the county's tourism industry is at 
last overcoming the stifling effects of last year's fires and the 1992 riots in 
Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
 "You see improvements in the underlying figures in the service sector and 
especially the tourism industry," Puri said. "It appears that this summer is 
finally bringing tourism back." 
</P>
<P>
 Monday's report showed a net loss of 3,900 non-agriculture jobs, however, from 
June, 1993, to June, 1994. 
</P>
<P>
 Services, government, transportation and public utilities each registered 
overall gains. But the manufacturing, finance, insurance, real estate, retail, 
wholesale and construction sectors registered net losses. The Summer Slump 
</P>
<P>
 Orange County's jobless rate increased slightly in June, but the upswing is 
typical during the summer. The current rate is still below the 1993 annual 
average of 6.7%. 
</P>
<P>
 June 1993: 7.1% 
</P>
<P>
 June 1994: 5.8% 
</P>
<P>
 Source: Employment Development Department 
</P>
</TEXT>
